      <h4 class="subtitle"> </h4> 
      <h1>Generate Fake Data for Your JavaScript Applications Using Faker</h1> 
      <div class="article__meta"> 
       <div class="meta__box"> 
        <a href="/@chris">Chris Sevilleja</a> 
        <a href="https://twitter.com/chrisoncode" target="_blank"> (@chrisoncode) </a> 
       </div> 
       <div class="meta__box"> 
        <time>January 19, 2015</time> 
       </div> 
       <div class="meta__box tags hidden-xs hidden-sm">

     <div class="columns is-desktop"> 
      <div class="article__content content column"> 
       <h2>Introduction</h2> 
       <p>When building out applications, we will often need data to show off how it works. It won't be much of an application if all our tables are blank!</p> 
       <p>Often, when we first start building out an application, we don't want to worry too much about the data. Having to create a database and fill it with sample data like users is an annoying step that is just in the way of creating an amazing app.</p> 
       <p>Luckily <a href="https://twitter.com/marak">Marak</a> has created a neat package that lets us create fake data on the fly: <a href="https://github.com/Marak/faker.js">faker</a>. </p> 
       <h2>A Quick Faker Example</h2> 
       <p>Let's say we wanted to create a user on the fly.</p> 
       <p>We want this user to have a <em>name</em>, <em>email</em>, <em>address</em>, <em>bio</em>, and even an <em>image</em>.</p> 
       <p>In Node, all we would have to do is:</p> 
       <pre><code class="language-javascript">
var user = {
  name: faker.name.findName(),
  email: faker.internet.email(),
  address: faker.address.streetAddress(),
  bio: faker.lorem.sentence(),
  image: faker.image.avatar()
};
</code></pre> 
       <p>Just like that, we have a whole user object that we can use within our application! The above will spit out:</p> 
       <pre><code class="language-javascript">
{
  "name": "Adaline Carroll",
  "email": "Albina.Ledner@gmail.com",
  "address": "545 Fritsch Locks",
  "bio": "dolorem officiis doloribus ut",
  "image": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/uifaces/faces/twitter/joelhelin/128.jpg"
}
</code></pre> 
       <p>Now we have a user and can move along with our application. No need to fuss about the database or populating it with fake users!</p> 
       <p>Let's learn a bit more about how to use this helpful package. </p> 
       <h2>Using Faker</h2> 
       <p>You can use faker from within your browser or on the server with Node.</p> 
       <p>From the <a href="https://github.com/Marak/faker.js">docs</a>, the installation instructions for both browser and Node are:</p> 
       <h3>Browser</h3> 
       <pre><code class="language-markup">
  &lt;!-- LOAD FAKER --&gt;
  &lt;script src="faker.js"&gt;

  &lt;script&gt;
    var name = faker.name.findName();
    var randomEmail = faker.internet.email();
  &lt;/script&gt;
</code></pre> 
       <h3>Node</h3> 
       <pre><code class="language-javascript">
  var faker = require('faker');

  var name = faker.name.findName();
  var randomEmail = faker.internet.email();
</code></pre> 
       <p>Super easy stuff. Let's run through the list of items that we can pull.</p> 
       <h2>Faker Data</h2> 
       <p>There is a huge amount of data that is able to be pulled. The overall category list is:</p> 
       <ul> 
        <li>name</li> 
        <li>address</li> 
        <li>phone</li> 
        <li>internet</li> 
        <li>company</li> 
        <li>image</li> 
        <li>lorem</li> 
        <li>helpers</li> 
        <li>date</li> 
        <li>random</li> 
        <li>hacker</li> 
       </ul> 
       <p>Each of those categories has a giant amount of options within itself. We won't go through them all, but an example is that for the <strong>name</strong> category, the following are available:</p> 
       <ul> 
        <li>name 
         <ul> 
          <li>firstName</li> 
          <li>lastName</li> 
          <li>findName</li> 
          <li>prefix</li> 
          <li>suffix</li> 
         </ul></li> 
       </ul> 
       <p>Each of these are accessible as a function. For instance:</p> 
       <pre><code class="language-javascript">
  // Chris
  var firstName = faker.name.firstName();

  // Sevilleja
  var lastName = faker.name.lastName();

  // Chris Sevilleja
  var findName = faker.name.findName();

  // Mr.
  var prefix = faker.name.prefix();

  // PhD
  var suffix = faker.name.suffix();
</code></pre> 
       <p>For a giant list of all the calls that are available through faker, check out the <a href="https://github.com/Marak/faker.js#api">API</a>.</p> 
       <h2>Helpers</h2> 
       <p>In addition to the many categories provided, faker also gives access to helpers. These are meant to make pulling data easier. Instead of picking one field here or there, these helpers can give a large amount of data that one would typically use in an application.</p> 
       <p>Here we'll give examples of the main helpers that are usable in our own applications:</p> 
       <h3>fakers.helpers.contextualCard()</h3> 
       <p>A user card that contains <em>name</em>, <em>username</em>, <em>avatar</em>, <em>email</em>, and <em>address</em>.</p> 
       <pre><code class="language-javascript">
{
  "name": "Kaleigh",
  "username": "Kaleigh60",
  "avatar": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/uifaces/faces/twitter/mbilderbach/128.jpg",
  "email": "Kaleigh6047@gmail.com",
  "dob": "1961-08-07T02:37:45.068Z",
  "phone": "113.601.0680",
  "address": {
    "street": "Myah Course",
    "suite": "Apt. 657",
    "city": "Boyerberg",
    "zipcode": "66413-8920",
    "geo": {
      "lat": "-44.6203",
      "lng": "16.7454"
    }
  },
  "website": "megane.biz",
  "company": {
    "name": "Little-Reinger",
    "catchPhrase": "Enhanced regional emulation",
    "bs": "interactive generate bandwidth"
  }
}
</code></pre> 
       <h3>fakers.helpers.userCard()</h3> 
       <p>A smaller card with less user information. This one doesn't come with a user avatar.</p> 
       <pre><code class="language-javascript">
{
  "name": "George Kohler",
  "username": "Emilio_Grady49",
  "email": "Aurore_Wintheiser90@gmail.com",
  "address": {
    "street": "Corwin Cove",
    "suite": "Suite 550",
    "city": "New Myah",
    "zipcode": "57817",
    "geo": {
      "lat": "-3.4045",
      "lng": "-16.7806"
    }
  },
  "phone": "1-806-338-0724 x844",
  "website": "katheryn.net",
  "company": {
    "name": "Purdy, Lesch and Jacobi",
    "catchPhrase": "Programmable incremental frame",
    "bs": "24/365 optimize initiatives"
  }
}
</code></pre> 
       <h3>fakers.helpers.createTransaction()</h3> 
       <pre><code class="language-javascript">
{
  "amount": "757.24",
  "date": "2012-02-02T08:00:00.000Z",
  "business": "Bahringer Group",
  "name": "Home Loan Account 5279",
  "type": "deposit",
  "account": "63843216"
}
</code></pre> 
       <h3>faker.helpers.createCard()</h3> 
       <p>The full might of the user card along with a section called <em>posts</em> that could help simulate blog articles.</p> 
       <pre><code class="language-javascript">
{

  "address": {

    "streetD": "Apt. 095",

    }
  },

  },

    "words": ["voluptatem", "quia", "ipsam"],

    "paragraph": "reiciendis exercitationem assumenda provident odionasperiores fugit officianperferendis exercitationem annam et eana ex autem ducimusnsint tenetur officia ratione nesciunt impedit qui"
  }, {

       <h2>Using in a Sample Node API</h2> 
       <p>We can create a quick Node API that returns fake data. As an example, if we wanted an API endpoint ot return user data, we can create:</p> 
       <pre><code class="language-javascript">
app.get('/api/user', function(req, res) {
  res.json({
    name: faker.name.findName(),
    email: faker.internet.email(),
    address: faker.address.streetAddress(),
    bio: faker.lorem.sentence(),
    image: faker.image.avatar()
  };
});
</code></pre> 
       <p>When our server is started, we can see this API endpoint when we use <a href="https://www.getpostman.com/">POSTman</a> to see our data come back in JSON form.</p> 
       <p><a href="https://cask.scotch.io/2015/01/node-faker-sample.jpg"><img src="https://cask.scotch.io/2015/01/node-faker-sample-748x500.jpg" alt="node-faker-sample" width="748" height="500" class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-6256 img-responsive img-thumbnail"></a></p> 
       <h2>Conclusion</h2> 
       <p>Hopefully this package will help you in your JavaScript development. This package helps to easily mock an API and return user information. You can get creative with it and even use this package for financial transactions.</p> 
       <p>I would encourage you to take a look at the <a href="http://marak.com/faker.js/">faker homepage</a> as well which helps you visualize the amount of data that comes out of this package.</p>
